To find the missing number from an unsorted array without using another array, you can use the XOR operation. XORing a number with itself results in 0. If you XOR all the elements in the array and then XOR the result with the XOR of all numbers from 1 to n (where n is the length of the array + 1), the result will be the missing number.

Here's a JavaScript function that demonstrates this approach:

javascript
Copy code
function findMissingNumber(arr) {
  const n = arr.length + 1;

  // XOR of all numbers from 1 to n
  let xor1ToN = 0;
  for (let i = 1; i <= n; i++) {
    xor1ToN ^= i;
  }

  // XOR of all elements in the array
  let xorArray = 0;
  for (let num of arr) {
    xorArray ^= num;
  }

  // The result is the missing number
  const missingNumber = xor1ToN ^ xorArray;

  return missingNumber;
}

// Example usage:
const numbers = [1, 4, 2, 6, 3]; // Assuming one number is missing from the sequence [1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6]
const missingNumber = findMissingNumber(numbers);
console.log("Missing Number:", missingNumber);
In this example, the findMissingNumber function takes an array of numbers and calculates the XOR of all numbers from 1 to n and the XOR of all elements in the array. The missing number is then found by XORing the two results.

This approach works because XORing all the elements that are present will cancel out those that are common between the two XOR operations, leaving only the missing number.